<HEADLINE>
FT  11 FEB 92 / Le Monde hit by FFr28m loss
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FRANCE'S independent daily newspaper Le Monde said yesterday it had lost
FFr28m (Pounds 2.86m) in 1991 because of a slump in advertising revenue, and
could only hope to break even this year, Reuter reports from Paris.
Director Jacques Lesourne said that despite a price increase and cuts in
staff and running costs the respected evening newspaper lost FFr13m more
than forecast. Its loss in 1990 was FFr39m.
'Our aim for 1992 is to break even,' Mr Lesourne wrote. He would be looking
for further ways of saving money without sacrificing quality or increasing
the cover price.
</TEXT>
