<HEADLINE>
FT  10 FEB 92 / Major calls for debate on policies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, IVO DAWNAY and RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR called yesterday for a switch in the focus of election
campaigning from the leading protagonists' private lives to the policy
divisions between their parties.
But after a weekend of clashes over alleged 'smear tactics' and 'dirty
tricks' there was little sign of any easing of the personal acrimony which
has come to dominate the campaign.
Mr Chris Patten, Conservative chairman, distanced his party from efforts by
some newspapers to delve into the personal lives of other opposition
politicians following last week's revelations by Mr Paddy Ashdown, the
Liberal Democrat leader, about an affair he had five years ago.
However, Mr Patten said politicians should not be too 'sanctimonious' about
intrusions into their private life if they used spouses and families to
project a favourable image. 'I don't like this sort of politics . . . but to
some extent we make a rod for our own back.'
Speaking on LBC radio, Mr Major said the general election should be 'a crisp
campaign that deals with the policies. I hope that will be the campaign the
other parties will fight'.
Meanwhile, Mr Ashdown complained that it was journalists, not himself, who
had wanted to write about his family life. However, he joined Mr Major in
opposing restrictions on press freedom.
For Labour, Mr Roy Hattersley, deputy leader, drew a stark contrast between
the 'ruthless individualism' of Tory polices and Labour's goal of 'a kinder,
gentler, more compassionate society'.
He told 800 local government delegates at a Blackpool conference that the
coming general election should be 'a crusade' based on the party's principle
of equality.
At the Young Conservative conference in Eastbourne, Mr Patten insisted that
the 'character' and 'leadership' issue was entirely legitimate.
The personal bitterness of the campaign so far was reflected in attacks
during the conference on Mr Gerald Kaufman, Labour's foreign affairs
spokesman, who has often led Labour's criticism of Mr Major and who was the
recipient of a continuous stream of jibes by senior ministers.
Mr Patten promised a sustained attack on Labour's tax and spending policies
and its general economic competence.
On Saturday, Mr Major set out the principal themes for the Conservative
manifesto as choice, ownership, opportunity and responsibility. He indicated
the government's determination to raise defence as an election issue by
announcing it would press ahead with an order for a fourth Trident nuclear
missile submarine.
However Mr Hattersley said the Tories could never understand voters'
'instinct for fairness'. He asked if Young Conservatives would have
'screamed with delight', as they did with the Trident announcement, 'if he
had said he was going to spend the same amount on the homeless, on schools
and on hospitals'.
Mr Patten brushed off an opinion poll giving Labour a 4-point lead. He said
other recent surveys gave the Tories an advantage confirming that the two
parties were 'neck and neck' at about 40 per cent.
</TEXT>
