<HEADLINE>
FT  10 FEB 92 / Lord Mayor backs change for Somerset House
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR BRIAN JENKINS, the Lord Mayor of London, will tonight launch a campaign
to make Somerset House a promotional showcase for London, John Willman
writes.
The 18th century building is the headquarters of the Inland Revenue and
houses parts of the Lord Chancellor's Department.
Both are due to vacate Somerset House soon. Mr Michael Heseltine, the
environment secretary, has invited suggestions for an 'imaginative public
use' of the building, which already houses the Courtauld Collection of fine
art.
Sir Brian is expected to say that London is alone among leading cities in
not having a promotional centre which would provide a showcase for business
opportunities, display available properties and offer information for those
wishing to set up in the capital.
The proposal will be backed by Westminster City Council and the London
Docklands Development Corporation.
As a first step, the Corporation of London, the local authority for the
City, is to launch an architectural exhibition in May in conjunction with
the Architectural Foundation. This will display all buildings in the City.
The exhibition - to be shown in the Royal Exchange - is designed to tour
European cities. But Sir Brian will propose that it be given a permanent
home in Somerset House and could be part of the showcase.
