<HEADLINE>
FT  10 FEB 92 / Global warming threat reaches council agendas
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN HUNT, Environment Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PLANNERS will have to consider the threat of global warming at local level
for the first time under planning guidelines to be announced today by Sir
George Young, minister for planning.
The guidelines would oblige councils to take account of the rising sea level
as a result of global warming when giving permission to build in low-lying
areas.
Sir George will also announce proposals that will encourage planners to take
account of public transport and to site housing so as to minimise car use
for journeys to work or school.
The government guidance will incorporate into local planning for the first
time the concept of protecting the environment through sustainable
development.
The intention is not to hold back economic growth, but to strike a balance
between growth and the environment.
The proposals involve greater use of public transport and improved energy
conservation as a means of curbinggreenhouse gases which cause global
warming.
Mr Tony Burton, senior planning officer for the Council for the Protection
of Rural England, said that the move was the most significant step to
incorporate wider environmental concerns into the UK planning system.
The proposals are in government guidance which has to be observed by county
councils in their strategic plans and by district councils in making local
development plans.
It would also have to be taken into consideration when hearing appeals by
developers against planning decisions.
Patterns of travel influence emissions of carbon dioxide, the main
greenhouse gas, and would have to be changed, the guidelines say. To reduce
emissions, new development should take place in locations which reduce the
need for car journeys and distances driven.
Policies should be designed to control pollution and limit nuisances such as
noise, smell and dirt, the guidelines add.
</TEXT>
