FT  10 FEB 92 / Lloyd's Names may step up legal action
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DEVELOPMENTS in the complex disputes between Lloyd's Names
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
the individuals whose assets back underwriting at insurance market - and the
agents who handle their affairs, are set to take a new twist in the next few
days.
With the ink barely dry on the out-of-court settlement ending the
long-running Warrilow dispute - and a similar outcome possible in the
mammoth action between 987 Names on Outhwaite syndicate 317/661 and more
than 80 agents - further litigation is on the cards.
A report - commissioned by Names and prepared by Rodney-Smith &amp; Partners,
the accountancy firm, will be published in the next 10 days - is likely to
provide new ammunition for Names on loss-stricken catastrophe reinsurance
syndicates. The report could lead the Names to seek injunctions to prevent
agents from drawing cash from their deposits. These are placed with the
agents when Names join Lloyd's and are drawn upon when Names fail to meet
cash calls from their other financial resources.
Such a move would spark confrontation with the authorities governing the
insurance market.
Agents announced in January that just more than Pounds 100m is needed from
syndicates managed by Gooda Walker within the next few weeks. Names on other
catastrophe syndicates could face similar calls.
Mr Alfred Doll-Steinberg, chairman of the Gooda Walker Names action group,
said last week that his members were becoming 'neurotic' about the threat to
call in bank guarantees.
The Rodney-Smith report, commissioned by the Gooda Walker and Rose Thompson
Young action groups, examines the 'spiral' reinsurance arrangements - in
which Lloyd's syndicates reinsure and retroinsure (the reinsurance of
reinsurance) each other's exposures to catastrophe risks. This formed the
bulk of business written by both groups.
According to Mr Martin Rodney-Smith the report lends 'strong support' to the
legal opinion obtained last October by Withers, the solicitors acting for
Gooda Walker Names, from Mr Gavin Lightman QC. Mr Lightman said that if it
were shown that the contracts were not in the interests of Names they could
be 'voidable'. This means that the contracts contain flaws which enable
Names to apply to have them set aside.
In his opinion Mr Lightman also stressed the importance of other parties to
the con-tract - who are other reinsurers - knowing that the contracts were
not in Names' interests.
Mr Rodney-Smith says that the report shows that the close-knit character of
the catastrophe reinsurance market means 'participants would have been aware
not only of the nature of each other's book of business but also, in all
probability if not certainty, of each other's reinsurance programme,'
'It was regular practice for syndicates to reinsure business in and reinsure
it out with the same syndicates,' he added.
If Mr Lightman agrees that the report does prove the case for 'voidability',
Names are likely to be advised to seek an injunction.
</TEXT>
