FT  10 FEB 92 / Moscow business centre wins backing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TWO initiatives to promote enterprise in central and eastern Europe have
been announced by the government. They are a business-support centre in
Moscow and a conference in London of employment ministers from 11 former
Communist states.
The first Russian support centre for small businesses will open in Moscow in
September with the help of finance provided by Britain's Know-How Fund, Mr
Michael Howard, employment secretary, said. The Pounds 50m fund was
established in 1989 to help countries in east and central Europe to develop
market-oriented economies.
The centre, which will provide advice and training to small-business owners
and would-be entrepreneurs, is intended to be the forerunner of a network
throughout Russia.
The announcement of the planned opening follows visits by British experts to
Moscow to provide advice on staffing the centre, staff training, the
availability of premises and equipment, and help with evaluating the needs
of entrepreneurs in Russia. A team of Russian experts paid a two-week return
visit to the UK, leaving for home last Saturday.
In a further move to help eastern European countries develop more
enterprising economies, the government has invited the employment ministers
from 11 countries to a conference in London this month.
Delegates will examine the political and practical difficulties of
establishing an enterprise culture and promoting the growth of small
companies. Hungary, Czechoslovakia, Poland, Russia, Ukraine, Kazakhstan and
the three Baltic states are expected to send delegates. The International
Labour Organisation and the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development
will also be represented.
Twenty managers from businesses in St Petersburg are due at Manchester
Business School today at the start of a four-week management development
programme. They come from businesses involved in boat building, hotel
construction, fashion knitwear and computer science.
