<HEADLINE>
FT  10 FEB 92 / Ministers go into battle over surcharges: A controversy
about poll tax that continues to dog the government's footsteps
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHO IS having to foot the bill for the poll-tax non-payers? 'The vast
majority of law-abiding citizens in this country - that's who', Mr Michael
Heseltine, the environment secretary, declaimed recently.
In the run-up to the general election, the government continues to be
haunted by controversy over the poll tax. In particular, the surcharge for
non-payment which is shown separately on poll-tax bills, has been the cause
of much anger among many voters.
While formally the surcharge appears on the bill as 'other adjustments'
which include items such as the revenue from the standard community charge
on second homes, it is broadly seen as the extra needed to make up for
non-payment.
Ministers and officials privately admit that this was a political and
presentational mistake. One minister said: 'It illustrates in microcosm the
basic problems with the poll tax.'
These problems are very visible, especially for a tax which raises so little
revenue. The poll tax itself has too high a profile, considering that it
raises only about 15 per cent - or under Pounds 10bn - of local-government
spending in England and less in Wales and Scotland.
The surcharge will raise only a fraction of that amount, yet it still has a
distinct identity as a separate charge. By contrast, VAT in 1990-91, its
last year at 15 per cent in raised Pounds 31bn.
The poll-tax surcharge is hard to collect. Beyond the familiar difficulty of
collecting a personal local tax when people regularly move house - which
helps to account for the existence of the surcharge in the first place - it
engenders particular resentment among those who do pay their poll tax.
It is difficult to assign blame for non-collection. For every time that Mr
Heseltine lambasts Labour councils' inefficiency, Labour can point to the
prime minister's own characterisation of the tax as 'virtually
uncollectable'.
Anecdotal evidence is already being produced about a new class of voters who
realise that they are being asked to subsidise non-payers and refuse to do
so.
One or two Tory MPs have been drawn close to making the moral case for not
paying. 'I see no reason why people who have paid their contribution to
local services should have to contribute to services for those who have
not,' one said during Commons discussion of the council tax.
The surcharge will ensure that some poll taxes will be forced over the
Pounds 300 mark, which is seen by many voters as an upper limit of
acceptability. Ministers have already admitted that their target poll tax of
Pounds 257 will be overshot.
The government estimates its target figure will be overshot by about Pounds
15 but that is lower than a forecast from the Chartered Institute of Public
Finance and Accountancy, representing most local authority treasurers, which
puts the overshoot at about Pounds 21.
The decision to show the level of surcharge so clearly on poll-tax bills
derives from the work of Mr David King, a senior economics lecturer at the
University of Stirling. When advising the government on the poll tax, he
made the case for greater transparency in bills.
At that time, with a much weaker regime for capping local expenditure,
ministers were concerned with council overspending rather than prospective
poll-tax non-collection.
Mr King's proposal to itemise charges was endorsed by Mr Michael Howard,
then local government minister. The belief - which remains unfulfilled - was
that when local taxpayers saw how much more they had to pay than the
government had planned, they would press their council to be more efficient.
It seems that the lesson of spelling out the surcharge has not been lost on
the government.
'You won't find a similar figure on the council-tax bill,' one minister
said.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 6
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-9792</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CBJBRACWFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920210
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 FEB 92 / PM outlines manifesto 'pillars'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR told Young Conservatives at the weekend that individual
choice, opportunity, ownership and responsibility would be the 'pillars' of
his manifesto.
Mr Chris Patten, party chairman, told the Young Conservatives' conference in
Eastbourne, that economic competence and taxation, defence and 'leadership'
would provide the core of the party's attack on Labour. His slogan was that
the Tories offered economic recovery and Labour permanent recession.
Some of the details have been held back to give substance to a
carefully-planned series of announcements over the next few weeks, but the
Conservatives have now marked out clearly the ground on which they intend to
fight the general election.
The themes would not have looked out of place in a manifesto crafted by Mrs
Margaret Thatcher, Mr Major's predecessor as prime minister and party
leader. But the government, Mr Major insisted, would never forget those who
had been 'knocked off' the ladder of opportunity or the need for a 'free'
National Heath Service.
The emphasis on individual choice which already runs through the
Conservatives' tax, education, and privatisation policies is to be
progressively strengthened in the approach to the election.
A white paper later this week on employment and training will signal a
further push to establish the primacy of the individual over collective
agreements in the workplace. There may also be proposals to extend to adults
the scheme to give individual training vouchers to the young unemployed.
A consultation paper next month will foreshadow a manifesto commitment to
break the local authorities' remaining grip on housing by the introduction
of compulsory competitive tendering for housing management.
There will also be further efforts to promote the Citizen's Charter as the
instrument through which individuals can assert their rights against the
state.
Mr Major edged back from a detailed plan for the privatisation of British
Rail, preferring to talk of the 'break-up' of the rail monopoly.
He foreshadowed a series of pledges to reinforce personal ownership.
Alongside a reduction in inheritance tax, the promise is for tax incentives
for share ownership and other savings and - the recession notwithstanding -
an attempt to extend the sale of council houses and flats.
Opportunity and responsibility are presented as the mirror image of the
drive for choice and ownership. Ownership will provide opportunity; choice
will confer responsibility.
The aim is to develop each of them in a detailed programme of announcements
planned for the next few weeks.
Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, will be expected to pull together many of
the strands in his Budget on March 10. If all goes to plan, Mr Major will
draw in the rest in a speech four days later at the Conservative Central
Council. That speech is intended to launch the election campaign proper.
</TEXT>
