<HEADLINE>
FT  10 FEB 92 / Self-rule supported 'by 31% of Scots'
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
FEWER THAN a third of Scottish voters support independence, according to a
Market Research Scotland poll in today's Scottish Daily Express. This
contrasts with a survey a week ago indicating that half of Scottish voters
wanted independence.
The latest poll shows 34 per cent supporting some form of devolution, 31 per
cent supporting outright independence, and 25 per cent favouring remaining
part of the United Kingdom, with 10 per cent 'don't knows'. Party
preferences where: Labour 41 per cent, Scottish National Party 29 per cent,
Conservatives 21 per cent, Liberal Democrat 8 per cent, and others 1 per
cent. The poll was conducted among 1,020 respondents between January 31 and
February 3.
Mrt Alex Salmond, Scottish National Party leader, said: 'We have more than
doubled our support since the last election.'
Mr John Major, the prime minister, is expected to visit Scotland within the
next few weeks as Conservatives try to rally voters behind the government's
opposition to a devolved Scottish assembly.
Mr Ian Lang, the Scottish secretary, said he thought it was impossible to
set up an assembly which would not lead to the end of Scotland's union with
England and Wales. Speaking on BBC Television Mr Lang also ruled out a
referendum on Scotland's future.
</TEXT>
