<HEADLINE>
FT  10 FEB 92 / Council tax in confusion, Blunkett says
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   THE TIMETABLE for the council tax
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
intended to be in force by April next year - has been jeopardised by the
need for a register of households, Labour said yesterday.
Mr David Blunkett, the party's local government spokesman, said 'the total
confusion' now emerging over the tax meant the Tories would be forced to
table additional legislation if they were returned to power. He was speaking
at Labour's local government conference in Blackpool, which ended yesterday
with the fervour of a pre-election rally.
Earlier in the conference, Mr Blunkett had said Labour would use its first
100 days in power to reverse 13 years of growing centralism in Whitehall
that had left the Department of the Environment 'riddled with Thatcherites'.
Yesterday, his attention centred on a report by local government
associations, discussed with environment department officials last week,
that expresses serious unease over the 'collectability' of the new tax.
The report, submitted by the associations of metropolitan, London and
district authorities, casts doubt on whether regulations now passing through
parliament give councils adequate powers to check households' eligibility
for discounts.
It also warns that, at the outset of the council-tax system, 'there will be
a resistance to the payment of local taxes as part of the legacy of the
community charge'.
In reply, environment department officials have said that steps will be
taken in the report stage of the bill later this month to empower councils
to seek information from households.
Mr Blunkett drew attention, however, to comments by a senior Department of
Environment official reported in a local government journal. The official is
quoted as warning that the legality of the use of the poll-tax register to
judge eligibility for council-tax discounts may have to be tested in the
courts.
'I suspect that if the Tories were re-elected further changes to the
legislation would be inevitable,' Mr Blunkett said.
That view is certain to be contested by ministers who have long promised
that the new tax will be enforced by April next year.
</TEXT>
