<HEADLINE>
FT  10 FEB 92 / Big market predicted for private mail service
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GOVERNMENT PLANS in the Citizen's Charter to open postal services to
competition will create a Pounds 500m market for letter services, according
to independent research published yesterday.
Dr Peter Rickard, former director of the Royal Mail letters network, says
the largest potential market will come from the proposal to reduce the
present Pounds 1 minimum postage fee which an independent letter service is
obliged to charge.
The market for a more reliable next-day letter service could exceed Pounds
200m, but only if the monopoly limit is brought down very close to the
first-class price, he says.
A highly reliable and profitable next-day service could be provided for
business-to-business mail at a modest price premium to first-class post.
Dr Rickard said yesterday that the threat to Royal Mail from private-sector
competition was real. But even if competitors built up a Pounds 500m market
this would still represent less than one-sixth of current mail volumes.
Losing one sixth of current mail volume would require Royal Mail to increase
prices by about 5 per cent. This would bring the price of delivery in real
terms to the level of five years ago.
Letter volumes had grown by 56 per cent since 1983 whereas postage rates had
fallen by 14 per cent in real terms. It was extremely unlikely that all
Royal Mail's first-class business-to-business mail would be lost, Dr Rickard
said.
The research indicates that if the loss was less than 3 per cent of the
total mail volumes each year - equivalent to the current loss of mail to
licensed document exchange operators - and allowing for general growth in
the market, Royal Mail's total volumes need not fall at all.
This would allow it to maintain economies of scale and avoid the need for
postal price increases.
Market Opportunities in the UK Letter Service, Rickard Johnson Management
Consultants, Dennis House, Hawley Rd, Hinckley, Leics LE10 OPR, Pounds
1,750.
</TEXT>
