<HEADLINE>
FT  10 FEB 92 / Venezuela leader stays firm under fire
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOE MANN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CARACAS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
VENEZUELA'S President Carlos Andres Perez has vowed to press on with
unpopular economic reforms despite last week's frustrated uprising by rebel
army units.
However, in his first press conference since the coup attempt, Mr Perez said
he was bringing forward a Dollars 4bn social welfare 'mega-project'.
Mr Perez admitted that economic benefits from the reforms had 'not trickled
down, way down'.
His government had, nevertheless, done more to protect the lower classes
through social programmes than any other Latin American nation undergoing
similar reforms. The shock, however, had been hardest for Venezuelans
accustomed to the easy wealth of the 1970s oil boom.
Mr Perez sought to justify heavy press censorship imposed since last week,
saying the country was still in a 'difficult period' in terms of public
order. The media should not 'make a star out of a felon', he said, referring
to Lt Col Hugo Chavez Frias, the leader of the revolt.
</TEXT>
