<HEADLINE>
FT  10 FEB 92 / Algeria's rulers declare state of emergency
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCIS GHILES and Agencies
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ALGERIA'S military-backed rulers, assuming new powers to crush widespread
unrest by Moslem fundamentalists, declared a state of emergency last night.
The Interior Ministry soon afterwards announced it would take steps to
dissolve the Islamic Salvation Front (FIS) for imperilling public order
through subversive actions.
Mr Mohamed Boudiaf, leader of the ruling High Council of State, decreed the
one-year emergency after at least 40 people were killed and more than 300
wounded in two days of fighting between security forces and FIS supporters.
About 400 people have been arrested.
The Moslem militants want a return to the electoral process cancelled last
month when the FIS looked set to win control of parliament.
Under the state of emergency all demonstrations are banned and local
authorities can order an end to all activities affecting public services.
The Algiers authorities had already banned a march called by the FIS for the
capital next Friday but the fundamentalist movement said it would go ahead
regardless.
The decree gives the interior minister power to close meeting places and
authorise the security forces to search houses day or night.
The authorities could use this provision to close mosques, which the FIS has
used to campaign against the new rulers.
The latest unrest erupted after weekly prayers on Friday, when security
forces tried to enforce a ban on FIS imams (mosque preachers) focusing on
politics.
State television said people threatening security could be taken before
military courts under the state of emergency. Local authorities can be
dissolved or their activities frozen, it added. The FIS controls more than
half the country's local authorities.
Workers taking part in unauthorised strikes can also be detained. The FIS
called a general strike last year as part of an earlier protest.
The FIS, in its last communique before Mr Boudiaf issued his decree, said
confrontation would continue with what it called 'the infernal apparatus of
repression'. Riot police shut down the movement's headquarters in Algiers
shortly afterwards and arrested five of the staff.
The FIS communique, signed by fugitive militant Abderrazak Rajam, demanded
that security forces lift their siege of Algerian mosques and allow freedom
of speech in them.
Scores of imams have been arrested for inflammatory speeches. The jailing of
one last Tuesday sparked three days of battles in the eastern town of Batna
in which 14 people died and 66 were wounded.
Two courthouses were set on fire in other towns during the last two days of
unrest.
Trouble continued in certain of the FIS strongholds in Algiers such as
Kouba, Badjarah and Hussein Dey throughout the weekend.
There was confusion last night as to whether Mr Tedjini Haddam, who is
rector of the Paris mosque, had resigned his position as a member of the
Council.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
