<HEADLINE>
FT  10 FEB 92 / Fall in global bank credit reversed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE first-ever fall in the amount of credit provided by the international
banking system has been reversed, according to the Bank for International
Settlements.
However, the latest figures show that renewed growth in net lending by banks
has been slow in the face of the slowdown in several big economies.
Net new lending in the third quarter of last year rose by Dollars 20bn
(Pounds 11bn), following a fall of Dollars 5bn in the second quarter. But
this growth amounted to just 12 per cent of the new lending in the
comparable period in 1990.
With activity in the international bond markets at about the same level as
in the second quarter, the total amount of new finance provided by the
global financial system in the three months to last September rose to
Dollars 60bn from Dollars 40bn.
Equity-linked bonds were the one area of the bond market to experience a
sharp decline, thanks to renewed weakness in the Tokyo stock market from
late summer. Only Dollars 11.8bn of equity-related bonds were issued,
against Dollars 18.6bn in the previous quarter. In the last three months of
the year the figure had collapsed to Dollars 4.6bn, BIS said.
</TEXT>
