<HEADLINE>
FT  10 FEB 92 / Observer: Poor example
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Meanwhile, I hear that Sir Frank Rogers, chairman of the Newspaper
Publishers Association, is a mite embarrassed by the activities of some of
his members.
For more than 20 years now, Sir Frank, who is also deputy chairman of the
Telegraph group, has been urging the newspaper industry to fight the
competition from TV by arguing the case for newspaper advertising
collectively. In November and December the industry spent Pounds 7m on more
than 140 full page ads with provocative copy lines such as ' Some people are
being conned by TV commercials. The people who pay for them.'
Unfortunately, some of Sir Frank's fellow publishers, led by the Mirror
Group, don't seem to have much faith in their own message. Last month was
almost certainly a record for newspaper spending on TV advertising.
</TEXT>
