<HEADLINE>
FT  10 FEB 92 / Output rise by small companies 'delayed'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN IMPROVEMENT in orders and output expected by smaller businesses four
months ago has yet to materialise, according to the latest Smaller Firms'
Economic Report from the Confederation of British Industry.
The report for last month confirms that businesses have consistently
underestimated the extent of the recession in manufacturing.
It shows that the rate of decline in output and orders for small businesses
slowed in the four months to last month, and that a further slowdown is
expected over the coming four months.
Mr Richard Brucciani, the new chairman of the CBI's Smaller Firms' Council,
said that the slowdown in the rate of decline was a positive sign, but the
growth in orders and output for which small businesses hoped still appeared
to be some way off. More small businesses are cutting investments in plant
and machinery although spending on training is set to rise, the report says.
Spending on product and process innovation is not expected to change.
It adds that cost pressures have remained weak and that unit costs will
continue to rise only very slowly in the coming months.
However, the expected increase in export orders has not occurred, and there
has been a rise in the number of businesses reporting a decline in overseas
orders. One in three companies cited the political and economic situation
abroad as constraining export orders, apparently reflecting difficulties in
the US and German economies.
Smaller Firms Economic Report. CBI, Centre Point, 103 New Oxford Street,
London WC1A 1DU. Pounds 5 (members) Pounds 10 (non-members).
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
