FT  08 FEB 92 / UK Company News: Clegg's Wace backer traced to South Africa
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP GAWITH, BARBARA DURR and BRONWEN MADDOX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE WOMAN who said she produced the original stake money used by Mr John
Michael Clegg to buy into the Wace Group said yesterday that it came from a
family inheritance.
Mr Clegg abruptly resigned last week as chief executive of Wace after market
speculation had linked the company to the Irish Republican Army.
The Wace Group is conducting a 'wide ranging inquiry' into all aspects of
the company. Mr Clegg denied the allegations but told Wace's board he was
leaving because of possible speculation about his family which might
embarrass the company. No evidence of links with the IRA has been found by
the security forces.
Wace, the company he built into the world's largest pre-press printing
specialist, has launched a wide ranging investigation covering the eight
years since he bought into the group using funds supplied by his cousin, Mrs
Jayne Riley.
Mrs Riley, formerly Miss Jayne Wright, was last night traced by the
Financial Times to a suburb of Durban, South Africa, where she lives with
her husband, Mr Keith Riley.
Mrs Riley confirmed she was Mr Clegg's cousin and that she had given him
about Pounds 700,000 to invest in her name.
Asked whether Mrs Riley would be prepared to put her account of events to
the Wace board, her husband replied: 'Of course she would. Why wouldn't she?
She has got nothing to hide.' She had not been in touch with Mr Clegg since
he resigned.
</TEXT>
