FT  08 FEB 92 / Mining equipment factory to close
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ANDERSON, the mining equipment subsidiary of Charter, the industrial holding
company, is to make 157 people redundant and close its plant at Bridgeton in
Glasgow. It will concentrate production at Motherwell, Lanarkshire, James
Buxton writes.
The Bridgeton plant, which employs 239 people, makes coalmine tunnelling
equipment. Some 97 people will lose their jobs there and the remaining 142
will be transferred to Motherwell, where 60 employees will also be made
redundant.
Mr Alasdair MacLaughlan, chief executive, blamed the further restructuring
on the halving of the number of coalfaces operated by British Coal.
