FT  08 FEB 92 / Nine die as clashes erupt in Algeria
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCIS GHILES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CLASHES between the security forces and supporters of the Islamic Salvation
Front (FIS) yesterday erupted in towns across Algeria after Friday prayers.
At least nine people were reported killed and scores injured. The clashes
were the most widespread and violent since the suspension of elections
nearly one month ago, after FIS candidates won 47 per of the popular vote.
The eastern capital of Constantine, the western seaport of Oran, Setif,
Tebessa, Sidi Bel Abbes and Tlemcen all witnessed violence.
Police and soldiers encircled mosques in FIS strongholds at dawn in Algiers
but this did not deter FIS militants from protesting for the fifth Friday in
succession. Two died and ten were wounded in the capital after dozens of
gendarmes swept down streets firing shots to dispersedemonstrators.
Black smoke was seen rising from FIS strongholds in Algiers, as
fundamentalists lit bonfires of used car tyres and built makeshift
barricades.
Last night, police and soldiers were holding hundreds inside Kouba mosque in
Algiers demanding that a fundamentalist who read an FIS communique before
prayers be turned over.
The French Interior Ministry said yesterday Mr Tedjini Haddam was resigning
from Algeria's five-man presidency. Mr Haddam, rector of the Paris Mosque,
had received complaints from France's Moslem community that the two posts
were incompatible.
</TEXT>
