<HEADLINE>
FT  08 FEB 92 / UN chief orders sweeping shake-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE UN secretariat announced a big shake-up last night, dropping fourteen
senior officials and scrapping a dozen departments and offices.
The sweeping changes were ordered by Secretary-General Boutros Boutros
Ghali, in response to demands by major cash contributors for a
rationalisation of the bloated bureaucracy.
However, Mr Boutros Ghali, by-passed a streamlining plan drafted by 30 UN
ambassadors led by Australia's Mr Peter Wilenski. This would have created a
small group of deputy secretaries general and eliminated an entire tier of
the hierarchy.
Mr Francois Giuliani, who is to continue as the UN spokesman, observed that
it was the secretary-general's prerogative to organise the secretariat as he
saw fit.
The Office for Political and General Assembly Affairs headed by Mr Ronald
Spiers, a former senior US State Department official, is among those to be
eliminated. Also to be scrapped is the Centre for Transnational
Corporations, which just this week issued a report critical of the handling
of the BCCI affair. The department was headed Mr Peter Hansen of Denmark.
Former Canadian broadcasting executive Mrs Therese Sevigny, one of the few
senior women, is to be replaced as under secretary-general for information
by Mr Eugeniusz Wyzner, a lawyer-diplomat who served the Polish communist
government before joining the UN staff 10 years ago as head of conference
services, another axed department.
Britain's Mr Marrack Goulding will head a new office of Peacekeeping
Operations, maintaining the responsibilities he held as a UN political
affairs executive. His office will also gain Mr Kofi Annan of Ghana, who
conducted the abortive talks with Iraq aimed at obtaining the resumption of
oil shipments.
Two key appointments - administration and management and emergency relief
co-ordinator - are to be announced, one of which may go to an American.
A newcomer is Mr Vladimir Petrovsky, former Soviet deputy foreign minister
who will be in charge of one of two political affairs departments. Mr James
Jonah of Sierra Leone, will head the other.
</TEXT>
