FT  08 FEB 92 / Russia and France agree partnership
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN DAVIDSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RUSSIA and France yesterday agreed on a new partnership based on
'confidence, solidarity and co-operation' in a treaty signed by President
Boris Yeltsin and President Francois Mitterrand at the end of a three-day
state visit by the Russian President, writes Ian Davidson from Paris.
Non-committally entitled 'Treaty between France and Russia', the agreement
effectively replaces the 'Franco-Soviet Treaty of Understanding and
Co-operation', which was signed with President Mikhail Gorbachev in October
1990, but never ratified.
The treaty promises co-operation on the conclusion of a European security
treaty and stresses the importance of nuclear disarmament, with the aim of
reducing nuclear arsenals to levels of 'minimal sufficiency'.
