FT  08 FEB 92 / International Company News: Molson ahead after nine months
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
HIGHER BEER sales in the US and a cleaning-services acquisition helped
Molson, the diversified Canadian brewer, lift net earnings to CDollars
110.4m (USDollars 94.3m) in the nine months to December 31, from CDollars
105.5m a year earlier, writes Bernard Simon in Toronto.
Per share earnings dropped from CDollars 1.99 to CDollars 1.97 as a result
of a share split last July. Sales rose to CDollars 2.25bn from CDollars
1.98bn. Interest expenses jumped to CDollars 43.2m from CDollars 19.7m.
Molson Breweries, a joint venture with Foster's Brewing of Australia, raised
operating earnings by 22 per cent to CDollars 136.3m. The figures exclude
the company's return on preferred shares and the amortisation of a deferred
gain arising from the 1989 brewing merger.
The company is the second biggest supplier of imported beer to the US, with
a market share last year of 17 per cent. Molson Breweries' share of the
Canadian market was steady at 52 per cent, but volume for the industry as a
whole declined by 1.7 per cent in the nine months.
Operating earnings of Diversey Corporation, Molson's cleaning-services unit,
jumped by 39 per cent to CDollars 50m.
</TEXT>
